---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="CRD ‚Äî Computational Relationship Dynamics">
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-badge">Research Paper ¬∑ Computational Social Science</div>
      <h1>
        Collision-Based Modeling of<br />
        <span class="accent">Romantic Pair Bonding</span>
      </h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        A computational framework for understanding relationship dynamics through
        large-scale simulation ‚Äî adapting methodologies from high-energy particle physics
        to the science of human connection.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href="/simulation" class="btn btn-primary">‚ñ∂ Launch Simulation</a>
        <a href="/methodology" class="btn btn-outline">Read Methodology</a>
      </div>

      <div class="hero-stats">
        <div class="hero-stat">
          <span class="hero-stat-value">10,000+</span>
          <span class="hero-stat-label">Pair Simulations</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-stat">
          <span class="hero-stat-value">20</span>
          <span class="hero-stat-label">Trait Dimensions</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-stat">
          <span class="hero-stat-value">3</span>
          <span class="hero-stat-label">Pairing Strategies</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-stat">
          <span class="hero-stat-value">50yr</span>
          <span class="hero-stat-label">Max Simulation Span</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Abstract -->
  <section class="section" id="abstract">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Abstract</h2>
      <p>
        We propose a novel computational framework for understanding romantic relationship
        formation and dynamics by adapting methodologies from high-energy particle physics.
        Just as particle colliders generate vast datasets by repeatedly colliding particles
        at varying energy levels to reveal fundamental interaction patterns, we model
        romantic relationships through large-scale simulations of pair bonding
        &ldquo;collisions&rdquo; across diverse parameter spaces.
      </p>
      <p>
        By creating synthetic populations with varying traits, preferences, and behavioral
        patterns, and simulating millions of potential pairings under different conditions,
        we extract fundamental principles governing relationship formation, stability, and
        dissolution. This approach promises to move relationship science from small-n
        observational studies toward a physics-inspired framework capable of revealing
        universal patterns through computational volume rather than physical observation.
      </p>

      <blockquote>
        <strong>Key insight:</strong> No single collision reveals the underlying physics.
        It&rsquo;s the <em>aggregate pattern</em> across millions of collisions that exposes
        the fundamental rules.
      </blockquote>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Analogy -->
  <section class="section" id="analogy">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>The Particle Collision Analogy</h2>
      <div class="analogy-grid">
        <div class="analogy-card">
          <div class="analogy-icon">‚öõÔ∏è</div>
          <div class="analogy-label">Physics</div>
          <div class="analogy-arrow">‚Üí</div>
          <div class="analogy-icon">üíë</div>
          <div class="analogy-label">Relationships</div>
        </div>
        <div class="mapping-list">
          <div class="mapping-row">
            <span class="map-from">Particles</span>
            <span class="map-sep">‚â°</span>
            <span class="map-to">Individuals (trait vectors)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="mapping-row">
            <span class="map-from">Collision</span>
            <span class="map-sep">‚â°</span>
            <span class="map-to">Pairing event</span>
          </div>
          <div class="mapping-row">
            <span class="map-from">Collision Energy</span>
            <span class="map-sep">‚â°</span>
            <span class="map-to">Relationship intensity</span>
          </div>
          <div class="mapping-row">
            <span class="map-from">Collision Products</span>
            <span class="map-sep">‚â°</span>
            <span class="map-to">Relationship outcomes</span>
          </div>
          <div class="mapping-row">
            <span class="map-from">Energy Levels</span>
            <span class="map-sep">‚â°</span>
            <span class="map-to">Contextual conditions</span>
          </div>
          <div class="mapping-row">
            <span class="map-from">Data Volume</span>
            <span class="map-sep">‚â°</span>
            <span class="map-to">Simulation scale</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Core Equations -->
  <section class="section" id="equations">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Mathematical Framework</h2>
      <p>The relationship evolves according to a system of differential equations:</p>

      <div class="eq-block">
        <div class="eq-label">Bond Strength Evolution</div>
        <div class="eq-body">
          dB/dt = &alpha;&middot;P(T&#x2081;, T&#x2082;, R(t)) &minus; &beta;&middot;N(T&#x2081;, T&#x2082;, R(t)) &minus; &gamma;&middot;B(t)
        </div>
        <div class="eq-desc">
          Where P = positive interactions (communication, empathy, shared values),
          N = negative interactions (conflict, neuroticism, avoidance),
          and &gamma;&middot;B represents natural bond decay.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="eq-block">
        <div class="eq-label">Satisfaction Evolution</div>
        <div class="eq-body">
          dS&#x2081;/dt = f&#x2081;(B(t), Match(T&#x2081;, T&#x2082;), E(t), H&#x2081;(t))
        </div>
        <div class="eq-desc">
          Individual satisfaction as a function of bond strength, partner preference matching,
          external context, and personal state.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="eq-block">
        <div class="eq-label">Dissolution Probability</div>
        <div class="eq-body">
          P(dissolve|t) = g(B(t), S&#x2081;(t), S&#x2082;(t), E(t), Barriers(t))
        </div>
        <div class="eq-desc">
          Stochastic dissolution based on investment model and interdependence theory.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="section cta-section">
    <div class="container" style="text-align:center;">
      <h2>Ready to Run the Simulation?</h2>
      <p style="color:var(--color-text-muted);max-width:500px;margin:0 auto 1.5rem;">
        Adjust population size, pairing strategy, stress levels, and equation parameters ‚Äî
        then watch the collision events unfold in real time.
      </p>
      <a href="/simulation" class="btn btn-primary" style="font-size:1.05rem;padding:0.75rem 2rem;">
        ‚ñ∂ Open Simulation Engine
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* Hero */
  .hero {
    padding: 5rem 0 3rem;
    background: radial-gradient(ellipse at 50% 0%, rgba(99,102,241,0.12) 0%, transparent 70%);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .hero-badge {
    display: inline-block;
    background: rgba(99,102,241,0.15);
    border: 1px solid rgba(99,102,241,0.35);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    padding: 0.3rem 0.8rem;
    border-radius: 99px;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .accent { color: var(--color-accent); }

  .hero-sub {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: 1rem 0 1.75rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .hero-actions {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .hero-stats {
    display: flex;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .hero-stat { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.2rem; }
  .hero-stat-value { font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-accent); }
  .hero-stat-label { font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); }

  /* Prose */
  .prose { max-width: 720px; }

  blockquote {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    padding: 0.75rem 1.25rem;
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    background: rgba(99,102,241,0.07);
    border-radius: 0 var(--radius) var(--radius) 0;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  /* Analogy */
  .analogy-grid {
    display: flex;
    gap: 3rem;
    align-items: flex-start;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .analogy-card {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1rem;
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    padding: 1.5rem 2rem;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .analogy-icon { font-size: 2rem; }
  .analogy-label { font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text); }
  .analogy-arrow { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--color-accent); }

  .mapping-list { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.6rem; }
  .mapping-row { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; font-size: 0.9rem; }
  .map-from { font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-accent); min-width: 140px; }
  .map-sep { color: var(--color-text-muted); }
  .map-to { color: var(--color-text); }

  /* Equations */
  .eq-block {
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 1.25rem 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .eq-label {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .eq-body {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: #a5b4fc;
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
  }

  .eq-desc {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .cta-section { border-bottom: none; }
</style>
